# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: neuron-biology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:neuron-biology/axon-terminal] Functionally, the axon terminal converts an electrical signal into a chemical signal.
[src:neuron-biology/axon-terminal] When an action potential arrives at an axon terminal (A), the neurotransmitter is released and diffuses across the synaptic cleft.
[src:neuron-biology/axon-terminal] If the postsynaptic cell (B) is also a neuron, neurotransmitter receptors generate a small electrical current that changes the postsynaptic potential.
[src:neuron-biology/axon-terminal] If the postsynaptic cell (B) is a muscle cell (neuromuscular junction), it contracts.
[src:neuron-biology/axon-terminal] Axon terminals are specialized to release neurotransmitters very rapidly by exocytosis.
[src:neuron-biology/axon-terminal] Neurotransmitter molecules are packaged into synaptic vesicles called quanta that cluster beneath the axon terminal membrane on the presynaptic side (A) of a synapse.
[src:neuron-biology/axon-terminal] Some of these vesicles are docked, i.e., connected to the membrane by several specialized proteins, such as the SNARE complex.
[src:neuron-biology/axon-terminal] The incoming action potential activates voltage-gated calcium channels, leading to an influx of calcium ions into the axon terminal.
[src:neuron-biology/axon-terminal] The SNARE complex reacts to these calcium ions.
[src:neuron-biology/axon-terminal] It forces the vesicle's membrane to fuse with the presynaptic membrane, releasing their content into the synaptic cleft within 180 μs of calcium entry.
[src:neuron-biology/axon-terminal] When receptors in the postsynaptic membrane bind this neurotransmitter and open ion channels, information is transmitted between neurons (A) and neurons (B).
[src:neuron-biology/axon-terminal] To generate an action potential in the postsynaptic neuron, many excitatory synapses must be active at the same time.
[src:neuron-biology/axon-terminal] Historically, calcium-sensitive dyes were the first tool to quantify the calcium influx into synaptic terminals and to investigate the mechanisms of short-term plasticity.
[src:neuron-biology/axon-terminal] The process of exocytosis can be visualized with pH-sensitive fluorescent proteins (Synapto-pHluorin): Before release, vesicles are acidic, and the fluorescence is quenched.
[src:neuron-biology/axon-terminal] Upon release, they are neutralized, generating a brief flash of green fluorescence.
[src:neuron-biology/axon-terminal] Another possibility is constructing a genetically encoded sensor that becomes fluorescent when bound to a specific neurotransmitter, e.g., glutamate.
[src:neuron-biology/axon-terminal] This method is sensitive enough to detect the fusion of a single transmitter vesicle in brain tissue and to measure the release probability at individual synapses.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] An **axon** (from Ancient Greek: ἄξων, romanized: **áxōn**, lit.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] 'axis'; also called a **nerve fiber** or **fibre**) is a long slender projection of a nerve cell or neuron found in most animals that typically conducts electrical impulses known as action potentials away from the nerve cell body.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The function of the axon is to transmit information to different neurons, muscles, and glands.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] In certain sensory neurons (pseudounipolar neurons), such as those for touch and warmth, the axons are called afferent nerve fibers and the electrical impulse travels along these from the periphery to the cell body and from the cell body to the spinal cord along another branch of the same axon.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Axon dysfunction can be the cause of many inherited and many acquired neurological disorders that affect both the peripheral and central neurons.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Vertebrate nerve fibers are classed into three types – group A nerve fibers, group B nerve fibers, and group C nerve fibers.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Groups A and B are myelinated, and group C is unmyelinated.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] These groups include both sensory fibers and motor fibers.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Another classification groups only the sensory fibers into four categories: Type I, Type II, Type III, and Type IV.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] An axon is one of two types of cytoplasmic protrusions from the cell body of a neuron; the other type is a dendrite.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Some types of neurons have no axon and transmit signals from their dendrites.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] In some species, axons can emanate from dendrites known as axon-carrying dendrites.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Axons are covered by a membrane known as an axolemma; the cytoplasm within an axon is called axoplasm.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Most axons branch, in some cases very profusely.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The end branches of an axon are called telodendria.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The swollen end of a telodendron is known as the axon terminal, or end-foot, which joins the dendrite or cell body of another neuron to form a synaptic connection.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Axons usually make contact with other neurons at junctions called synapses, but they can also make contact with muscle or gland cells.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] In some circumstances, the axon of one neuron may form a synapse with the dendrites of the same neuron, resulting in an autapse.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] At a synapse, the membrane of the axon closely adjoins the membrane of the target cell, and special molecular structures serve to transmit electrical or electrochemical signals across the gap.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Some synaptic junctions appear along the length of an axon as it extends; these are called *en passant boutons* ("in passing boutons") and can be in the hundreds or even the thousands along one axon.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Other synapses appear as terminals at the ends of axonal branches.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] A single axon, with all its branches taken together, can target multiple parts of the brain and generate thousands of synaptic terminals.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] A bundle of axons makes a nerve tract in the central nervous system, and a fascicle in the peripheral nervous system.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] In placental mammals, the largest white matter tract in the brain is the corpus callosum, formed of some 200 million axons in the human brain.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Axons are the primary transmission lines of the nervous system, and as bundles they form nerves in the peripheral nervous system, or nerve tracts in the central nervous system (CNS).
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Some axons can extend up to one meter or more while others extend as little as one millimeter.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The longest axons in the human body are those of the sciatic nerve, which run from the base of the spinal cord to the big toe of each foot.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Most individual axons are microscopic in diameter (typically about one micrometer (μm) across).
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The largest mammalian axons can reach a diameter of up to 20 μm.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The squid giant axon, which is specialized to conduct signals very rapidly, is close to 1 millimeter in diameter, the size of a small pencil lead.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The numbers of axonal telodendria (the branching structures at the end of the axon) can also differ from one nerve fiber to the next.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Axons in the CNS typically show multiple telodendria, with many synaptic end points.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] In comparison, the cerebellar granule cell axon is characterized by a single T-shaped branch node from which two parallel fibers extend.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Elaborate branching allows for the simultaneous transmission of messages to a large number of target neurons within a single region of the brain.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] There are two types of axons in the nervous system: myelinated and unmyelinated axons.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Myelin is a layer of a fatty insulating substance, which is formed by two types of glial cells: Schwann cells and oligodendrocytes.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] In the peripheral nervous system Schwann cells form the myelin sheath of a myelinated axon.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Oligodendrocytes form the insulating myelin in the CNS.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Along myelinated nerve fibers, gaps in the myelin sheath known as nodes of Ranvier occur at evenly spaced intervals.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The myelination enables an especially rapid mode of electrical impulse propagation called saltatory conduction.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The myelinated axons from the cortical neurons form the bulk of the neural tissue called white matter in the brain.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The myelin gives the white appearance to the tissue in contrast to the grey matter of the cerebral cortex which contains the neuronal cell bodies.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] A similar arrangement is seen in the cerebellum.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Bundles of myelinated axons make up the nerve tracts in the CNS, and where they cross the midline of the brain to connect opposite regions they are called commissures.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The largest of these is the corpus callosum that connects the two cerebral hemispheres, and this has around 20 million axons.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The structure of a neuron is seen to consist of two separate functional regions, or compartments – the cell body together with the dendrites as one region, and the axonal region as the other.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The axonal region or compartment, includes the axon hillock, the initial segment, the rest of the axon, and the axon telodendria, and axon terminals.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The Nissl bodies that produce the neuronal proteins are absent in the axonal region.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Proteins needed for the growth of the axon, and the removal of waste materials, need a framework for transport.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] This axonal transport is provided for in the axoplasm by arrangements of microtubules and type IV intermediate filaments known as neurofilaments.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The axon hillock is the area formed from the cell body of the neuron as it extends to become the axon.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The received action potentials that are summed in the neuron are transmitted to the axon hillock for the generation of an action potential from the initial segment.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The **axonal initial segment** (AIS) is a structurally and functionally separate microdomain of the axon.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] One function of the initial segment is to separate the main part of an axon from the rest of the neuron; another function is to help initiate action potentials.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Both of these functions support neuron cell polarity, in which dendrites (and, in some cases the soma) of a neuron receive input signals at the basal region, and at the apical region the neuron's axon provides output signals.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The axon initial segment is unmyelinated and contains a specialized complex of proteins.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] It is between approximately 20 and 60 μm in length and functions as the site of action potential initiation.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Both the position on the axon and the length of the AIS can change showing a degree of plasticity that can fine-tune the neuronal output.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] A longer AIS is associated with a greater excitability.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Plasticity is also seen in the ability of the AIS to change its distribution and to maintain the activity of neural circuitry at a constant level.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The AIS is highly specialized for the fast conduction of nerve impulses.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] This is achieved by a high concentration of voltage-gated sodium channels in the initial segment where the action potential is initiated.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The ion channels are accompanied by a high number of cell adhesion molecules and scaffold proteins that anchor them to the cytoskeleton.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Interactions with ankyrin-G are important as it is the major organizer in the AIS.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] In other cases as seen in rat studies an axon originates from a dendrite; such axons are said to have "dendritic origin".
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Some axons with dendritic origin similarly have a "proximal" initial segment that starts directly at the axon origin, while others have a "distal" initial segment, discernibly separated from the axon origin.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] In many species some of the neurons have axons that emanate from the dendrite and not from the cell body, and these are known as axon-carrying dendrites.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] In many cases, an axon originates at an axon hillock on the soma; such axons are said to have "somatic origin".
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Some axons with somatic origin have a "proximal" initial segment adjacent the axon hillock, while others have a "distal" initial segment, separated from the soma by an extended axon hillock.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The axoplasm is the equivalent of cytoplasm in the cell.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Microtubules form in the axoplasm at the axon hillock.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] They are arranged along the length of the axon, in overlapping sections, and all point in the same direction – towards the axon terminals.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] This is noted by the positive endings of the microtubules.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] This overlapping arrangement provides the routes for the transport of different materials from the cell body.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Studies on the axoplasm has shown the movement of numerous vesicles of all sizes to be seen along cytoskeletal filaments – the microtubules, and neurofilaments, in both directions between the axon and its terminals and the cell body.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Outgoing anterograde transport from the cell body along the axon, carries mitochondria and membrane proteins needed for growth to the axon terminal.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Ingoing retrograde transport carries cell waste materials from the axon terminal to the cell body.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Outgoing and ingoing tracks use different sets of motor proteins.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Outgoing transport is provided by kinesin, and ingoing return traffic is provided by dynein.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] There are many forms of kinesin and dynein motor proteins, and each is thought to carry a different cargo.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The studies on transport in the axon led to the naming of kinesin.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] In the nervous system, axons may be myelinated, or unmyelinated.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] This is the provision of an insulating layer, called a myelin sheath.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The myelin membrane is unique in its relatively high lipid to protein ratio.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] In the peripheral nervous system axons are myelinated by glial cells known as Schwann cells.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] In the central nervous system the myelin sheath is provided by another type of glial cell, the oligodendrocyte.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] An oligodendrocyte can myelinate up to 50 axons.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The composition of myelin is different in the two types.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] In the CNS the major myelin protein is proteolipid protein, and in the PNS it is myelin basic protein.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Nodes of Ranvier (also known as *myelin sheath gaps*) are short unmyelinated segments of a myelinated axon, which are found periodically interspersed between segments of the myelin sheath.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Therefore, at the point of the node of Ranvier, the axon is reduced in diameter.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] These nodes are areas where action potentials can be generated.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] In saltatory conduction, electrical currents produced at each node of Ranvier are conducted with little attenuation to the next node in line, where they remain strong enough to generate another action potential.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Thus in a myelinated axon, action potentials effectively "jump" from node to node, bypassing the myelinated stretches in between, resulting in a propagation speed much faster than even the fastest unmyelinated axon can sustain.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] An axon can divide into many branches called telodendria (Greek for 'end of tree').
[src:neuron-biology/axon] At the end of each **telodendron** is an axon terminal (also called a terminal bouton or synaptic bouton, or end-foot).
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Axon terminals contain synaptic vesicles that store the neurotransmitter for release at the synapse.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] This makes multiple synaptic connections with other neurons possible.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Sometimes the axon of a neuron may synapse onto dendrites of the same neuron, when it is known as an autapse.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Some synaptic junctions appear along the length of an axon as it extends; these are called **en passant boutons** ("in passing boutons") and can be in the hundreds or even the thousands along one axon.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] In the normally developed brain, along the shaft of some axons are located pre-synaptic boutons also known as **axonal varicosities** and these have been found in regions of the hippocampus that function in the release of neurotransmitters.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] However, axonal varicosities are also present in neurodegenerative diseases where they interfere with the conduction of an action potential.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Axonal varicosities are also the hallmark of traumatic brain injuries.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Axonal damage is usually to the axon cytoskeleton disrupting transport.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] As a consequence protein accumulations such as amyloid-beta precursor protein can build up in a swelling resulting in a number of varicosities along the axon.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Most axons carry signals in the form of action potentials, which are discrete electrochemical impulses that travel rapidly along an axon, starting at the cell body and terminating at points where the axon makes synaptic contact with target cells.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The defining characteristic of an action potential is that it is "all-or-nothing" – every action potential that an axon generates has essentially the same size and shape.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] This all-or-nothing characteristic allows action potentials to be transmitted from one end of a long axon to the other without any reduction in size.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] There are, however, some types of neurons with short axons that carry graded electrochemical signals, of variable amplitude.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] When an action potential reaches a presynaptic terminal, it activates the synaptic transmission process.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The first step is rapid opening of calcium ion channels in the membrane of the axon, allowing calcium ions to flow inward across the membrane.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The resulting increase in intracellular calcium concentration causes synaptic vesicles (tiny containers enclosed by a lipid membrane) filled with a neurotransmitter chemical to fuse with the axon's membrane and empty their contents into the extracellular space.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The neurotransmitter is released from the presynaptic nerve through exocytosis.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The neurotransmitter chemical then diffuses across to receptors located on the membrane of the target cell.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The neurotransmitter binds to these receptors and activates them.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Depending on the type of receptors that are activated, the effect on the target cell can be to excite the target cell, inhibit it, or alter its metabolism in some way.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] This entire sequence of events often takes place in less than a thousandth of a second.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Afterward, inside the presynaptic terminal, a new set of vesicles is moved into position next to the membrane, ready to be released when the next action potential arrives.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The action potential is the final electrical step in the integration of synaptic messages at the scale of the neuron.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Extracellular recordings of action potential propagation in axons has been demonstrated in freely moving animals.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] While extracellular somatic action potentials have been used to study cellular activity in freely moving animals such as place cells, axonal activity in both white and gray matter can also be recorded.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Extracellular recordings of axon action potential propagation is distinct from somatic action potentials in three ways: 1.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The signal has a shorter peak-trough duration (~150μs) than of pyramidal cells (~500μs) or interneurons (~250μs).
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Activity recorded on a tetrode is seen on only one of the four recording wires.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] In recordings from freely moving rats, axonal signals have been isolated in white matter tracts including the alveus and the corpus callosum as well hippocampal gray matter.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] In fact, the generation of action potentials in vivo is sequential in nature, and these sequential spikes constitute the digital codes in the neurons.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Although previous studies indicate an axonal origin of a single spike evoked by short-term pulses, physiological signals in vivo trigger the initiation of sequential spikes at the cell bodies of the neurons.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] In addition to propagating action potentials to axonal terminals, the axon is able to amplify the action potentials, which makes sure a secure propagation of sequential action potentials toward the axonal terminal.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] In terms of molecular mechanisms, voltage-gated sodium channels in the axons possess lower threshold and shorter refractory period in response to short-term pulses.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The development of the axon to its target, is one of the six major stages in the overall development of the nervous system.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Studies done on cultured hippocampal neurons suggest that neurons initially produce multiple neurites that are equivalent, yet only one of these neurites is destined to become the axon.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] It is unclear whether axon specification precedes axon elongation or vice versa, although recent evidence points to the latter.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] If an axon that is not fully developed is cut, the polarity can change and other neurites can potentially become the axon.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] This alteration of polarity only occurs when the axon is cut at least 10 μm shorter than the other neurites.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] After the incision is made, the longest neurite will become the future axon and all the other neurites, including the original axon, will turn into dendrites.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Imposing an external force on a neurite, causing it to elongate, will make it become an axon.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Nonetheless, axonal development is achieved through a complex interplay between extracellular signaling, intracellular signaling and cytoskeletal dynamics.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The extracellular signals that propagate through the extracellular matrix surrounding neurons play a prominent role in axonal development.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] These signaling molecules include proteins, neurotrophic factors, and extracellular matrix and adhesion molecules.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Netrin (also known as UNC-6) a secreted protein, functions in axon formation.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] When the UNC-5 netrin receptor is mutated, several neurites are irregularly projected out of neurons and finally a single axon is extended anteriorly.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The neurotrophic factors – nerve growth factor (NGF), brain-derived neurotrophic factor (BDNF) and neurotrophin-3 (NTF3) are also involved in axon development and bind to Trk receptors.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The ganglioside-converting enzyme plasma membrane ganglioside sialidase (PMGS), which is involved in the activation of TrkA at the tip of neutrites, is required for the elongation of axons.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] PMGS asymmetrically distributes to the tip of the neurite that is destined to become the future axon.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] During axonal development, the activity of PI3K is increased at the tip of destined axon.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Disrupting the activity of PI3K inhibits axonal development.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Activation of PI3K results in the production of phosphatidylinositol (3,4,5)-trisphosphate (PtdIns) which can cause significant elongation of a neurite, converting it into an axon.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] As such, the overexpression of phosphatases that dephosphorylate PtdIns leads into the failure of polarization.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The neurite with the lowest actin filament content will become the axon.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] PGMS concentration and f-actin content are inversely correlated; when PGMS becomes enriched at the tip of a neurite, its f-actin content is substantially decreased.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] In addition, exposure to actin-depolimerizing drugs and toxin B (which inactivates Rho-signaling) causes the formation of multiple axons.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Consequently, the interruption of the actin network in a growth cone will promote its neurite to become the axon.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Growing axons move through their environment via the growth cone, which is at the tip of the axon.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The growth cone has a broad sheet-like extension called a lamellipodium which contain protrusions called filopodia.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The filopodia are the mechanism by which the entire process adheres to surfaces and explores the surrounding environment.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Actin plays a major role in the mobility of this system.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Environments with high levels of cell adhesion molecules (CAMs) create an ideal environment for axonal growth.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] This seems to provide a "sticky" surface for axons to grow along.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Examples of CAMs specific to neural systems include N-CAM, TAG-1 – an axonal glycoprotein – and MAG, all of which are part of the immunoglobulin superfamily.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Another set of molecules called extracellular matrix-adhesion molecules also provide a sticky substrate for axons to grow along.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Examples of these molecules include laminin, fibronectin, tenascin, and perlecan.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Some of these are surface bound to cells and thus act as short range attractants or repellents.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Others are difusible ligands and thus can have long range effects.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Cells called guidepost cells assist in the guidance of neuronal axon growth.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] These cells that help axon guidance, are typically other neurons that are sometimes immature.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] When the axon has completed its growth at its connection to the target, the diameter of the axon can increase by up to five times, depending on the speed of conduction required.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] It has also been discovered through research that if the axons of a neuron were damaged, as long as the soma (the cell body of a neuron) is not damaged, the axons would regenerate and remake the synaptic connections with neurons with the help of guidepost cells.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] This is also referred to as neuroregeneration.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Nogo-A is a type of neurite outgrowth inhibitory component that is present in the central nervous system myelin membranes (found in an axon).
[src:neuron-biology/axon] It has a crucial role in restricting axonal regeneration in adult mammalian central nervous system.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] In recent studies, if Nogo-A is blocked and neutralized, it is possible to induce long-distance axonal regeneration which leads to enhancement of functional recovery in rats and mouse spinal cord.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] A recent study has also found that macrophages activated through a specific inflammatory pathway activated by the Dectin-1 receptor are capable of promoting axon recovery, also however causing neurotoxicity in the neuron.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Axons vary largely in length from a few micrometers up to meters in some animals.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] This emphasizes that there must be a cellular length regulation mechanism allowing the neurons both to sense the length of their axons and to control their growth accordingly.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] It was discovered that motor proteins play an important role in regulating the length of axons.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Based on this observation, researchers developed an explicit model for axonal growth describing how motor proteins could affect the axon length on the molecular level.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] These studies suggest that motor proteins carry signaling molecules from the soma to the growth cone and vice versa whose concentration oscillates in time with a length-dependent frequency.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The axons of neurons in the human peripheral nervous system can be classified based on their physical features and signal conduction properties.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Axons were known to have different thicknesses (from 0.1 to 20 μm) and these differences were thought to relate to the speed at which an action potential could travel along the axon – its *conductance velocity*.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Erlanger and Gasser proved this hypothesis, and identified several types of nerve fiber, establishing a relationship between the diameter of an axon and its nerve conduction velocity.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] They published their findings in 1941 giving the first classification of axons.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The first one introduced by Erlanger and Gasser, grouped the fibers into three main groups using the letters A, B, and C.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] These groups, group A, group B, and group C include both the sensory fibers (afferents) and the motor fibers (efferents).
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The first group A, was subdivided into alpha, beta, gamma, and delta fibers – Aα, Aβ, Aγ, and Aδ.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The motor neurons of the different motor fibers, were the lower motor neurons – alpha motor neuron, beta motor neuron, and gamma motor neuron having the Aα, Aβ, and Aγ nerve fibers, respectively.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Later findings by other researchers identified two groups of Aa fibers that were sensory fibers.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] These were then introduced into a system (Lloyd classification) that only included sensory fibers (though some of these were mixed nerves and were also motor fibers).
[src:neuron-biology/axon] This system refers to the sensory groups as Types and uses Roman numerals: Type Ia, Type Ib, Type II, Type III, and Type IV.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Different sensory receptors are innervated by different types of nerve fibers.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Proprioceptors are innervated by type Ia, Ib and II sensory fibers, mechanoreceptors by type II and III sensory fibers and nociceptors and thermoreceptors by type III and IV sensory fibers.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] In order of degree of severity, injury to a nerve in the peripheral nervous system can be described as neurapraxia, axonotmesis, or neurotmesis.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Concussion is considered a mild form of diffuse axonal injury.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Axonal injury can also cause central chromatolysis.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The dysfunction of axons in the nervous system is one of the major causes of many inherited and acquired neurological disorders that affect both peripheral and central neurons.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] When an axon is crushed, an active process of axonal degeneration takes place at the part of the axon furthest from the cell body.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] This degeneration takes place quickly following the injury, with the part of the axon being sealed off at the membranes and broken down by macrophages.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] This is known as Wallerian degeneration.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Dying back of an axon can also take place in many neurodegenerative diseases, particularly when axonal transport is impaired, this is known as Wallerian-like degeneration.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Studies suggest that the degeneration happens as a result of the axonal protein NMNAT2, being prevented from reaching all of the axon.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Demyelination of axons causes the multitude of neurological symptoms found in the disease multiple sclerosis.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Dysmyelination is the abnormal formation of the myelin sheath.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] This is implicated in several leukodystrophies, and also in schizophrenia.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] A severe traumatic brain injury can result in widespread lesions to nerve tracts damaging the axons in a condition known as diffuse axonal injury.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] This can lead to a persistent vegetative state.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] It has been shown in studies on the rat that axonal damage from a single mild traumatic brain injury, can leave a susceptibility to further damage, after repeated mild traumatic brain injuries.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] A nerve guidance conduit is an artificial means of guiding axon growth to enable neuroregeneration, and is one of the many treatments used for different kinds of nerve injury.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Some general dictionaries define "nerve fiber" as any neuronal process, including both axons and dendrites.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] However, medical sources generally use "nerve fiber" to refer to the axon only.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] German anatomist Otto Friedrich Karl Deiters is generally credited with the discovery of the axon by distinguishing it from the dendrites.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Swiss Rüdolf Albert von Kölliker and German Robert Remak were the first to identify and characterize the axon initial segment.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Louis-Antoine Ranvier was the first to describe the gaps or nodes found on axons and for this contribution these axonal features are now commonly referred to as the nodes of Ranvier.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Santiago Ramón y Cajal, a Spanish anatomist, proposed that axons were the output components of neurons, describing their functionality.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Joseph Erlanger and Herbert Gasser earlier developed the classification system for peripheral nerve fibers, based on axonal conduction velocity, myelination, fiber size etc.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Alan Hodgkin and Andrew Huxley also employed the squid giant axon (1939) and by 1952 they had obtained a full quantitative description of the ionic basis of the action potential, leading to the formulation of the Hodgkin–Huxley model.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Hodgkin and Huxley were awarded jointly the Nobel Prize for this work in 1963.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The formulae detailing axonal conductance were extended to vertebrates in the Frankenhaeuser–Huxley equations.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The understanding of the biochemical basis for action potential propagation has advanced further, and includes many details about individual ion channels.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The axons in invertebrates have been extensively studied.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The longfin inshore squid, often used as a model organism has the longest known axon.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] The giant squid has the largest axon known.
[src:neuron-biology/axon] Its size ranges from 0.5 (typically) to 1 mm in diameter and is used in the control of its jet propulsion system.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] A **dendrite** (from Greek δένδρον *déndron*, "tree") or **dendron** is a branched cytoplasmic process extending from a nerve cell; it propagates the electrochemical stimulation received from other neural cells to the cell body, or soma, of the neuron from which the dendrites project.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Electrical stimulation is transmitted onto dendrites by upstream neurons (usually via their axons) via synapses which are located at various points throughout the dendritic tree.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Dendrites play a critical role in integrating these synaptic inputs and in determining the extent to which action potentials are produced by the neuron.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Dendrites are one of two types of cytoplasmic processes that extrude from the cell body of a neuron, the other type being an axon.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Axons can be distinguished from dendrites by several features including shape, length, and function.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Dendrites often taper off in shape and are shorter, while axons tend to maintain a constant radius and can be very long.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Typically, axons transmit electrochemical signals while dendrites receive the electrochemical signals, although, some types of neurons in certain species lack specialized axons and transmit signals via their dendrites.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Dendrites provide an enlarged surface area to receive signals from axon terminals of other neurons.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] The dendrite of a large pyramidal cell receives signals from about 30,000 presynaptic neurons.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Excitatory synapses terminate on dendritic spines, tiny protrusions from the dendrite with a high density of neurotransmitter receptors.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Most inhibitory synapses directly contact the dendritic shaft.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Synaptic activity causes local changes in the electrical potential across the plasma membrane of the dendrite.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] This change in membrane potential will passively spread along the dendrite, but becomes weaker with distance without an action potential.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] To generate an action potential, many excitatory synapses have to be active at the same time, leading to strong depolarization of the dendrite and the cell body (soma).
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] The action potential, which typically starts at the axon hillock, propagates down the length of the axon to the axon terminals where it triggers the release of neurotransmitters.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Furthermore, if the signal moves backwards into the dendrite, it is retrograde propagation, which provides an important signal for spike-timing-dependent plasticity (STDP).
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Most synapses are axodendritic, involving an axon signaling to a dendrite.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] There are also dendrodendritic synapses, signaling from one dendrite to another.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] An autapse is a synapse in which the axon of one neuron transmits signals to its own dendrite.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] The general structure of the dendrite is used to classify neurons into multipolar, bipolar, and unipolar types.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Multipolar neurons are composed of one axon and many dendritic trees.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Pyramidal cells are multipolar cortical neurons with pyramid-shaped cell bodies and large dendrites that extend towards the surface of the cortex (apical dendrite).
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Bipolar neurons have two main dendrites at opposing ends of the cell body.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Many inhibitory neurons have this morphology.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Unipolar neurons, typical for insects, have a stalk that extends from the cell body, separating into two branches with one containing the dendrites and the other with the terminal buttons.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] In vertebrates, sensory neurons detecting touch or temperature are unipolar.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Dendritic branching can be extensive and in some cases is sufficient to receive as many as 100,000 inputs to a single neuron.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Neurons grow dendrites in highly specific shapes that determine which inputs are received and processed; in simple terms: structure leads to function.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Additionally, small molecular changes can have a significant change in functions that can contribute to developmental disorders.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Different dendritic cell types use mechanisms in distinct ways to generate diverse dendritic trees that connect the nervous system.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Specific lipids are important in the process of mechanisms in dendrites.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Glycerophospholipids and their interacting proteins are a specific lipid that is crucial in the initiation and elongation that is involved in the growth of dendritic spines and branches.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] While the mechanism that supports dendritic branching isn't entirely understood, phosphoinositides (PIPs) in the plasma membrane have been found to be a key factor in shaping dendrites by downstream signaling.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] The term *dendrites* was first used in 1889 by Wilhelm His to describe the number of smaller "protoplasmic processes" that were attached to a nerve cell.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] German anatomist, Otto Friedrich Karl Deiters, is generally credited with the discovery of the axon by distinguishing it from the dendrites.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Some of the first intracellular recordings in a nervous system were made in the late 1930s by Kenneth S.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Swiss Rüdolf Albert von Kölliker and German Robert Remak were the first to identify and characterize the axonal initial segment.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Alan Hodgkin and Andrew Huxley also employed the squid giant axon in 1939, and by 1952, they had obtained a full quantitative description of the ionic basis of the action potential, leading to the formulation of the Hodgkin–Huxley model.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Hodgkin and Huxley were jointly awarded the Nobel Prize for this work in 1963.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] The formulas detailing axonal conductance were extended to vertebrates in the Frankenhaeuser–Huxley equations.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Louis-Antoine Ranvier was the first to describe the gaps or nodes found on axons and for this contribution, these axonal features are now commonly referred to as the Nodes of Ranvier.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Santiago Ramón y Cajal, a Spanish anatomist, proposed that axons were the output components of neurons.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] He also proposed that neurons were discrete cells that communicated with each other via specialized junctions, or spaces between cells, now known as a synapse.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Ramón y Cajal improved a silver staining process known as Golgi's method, which had been developed by his rival, Camillo Golgi.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] During the development of dendrites, several factors can influence differentiation.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] These include modulation of sensory input, environmental pollutants, body temperature, and drug use.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] For example, rats raised in dark environments were found to have a reduced number of spines in their pyramidal cells located in the primary visual cortex and a marked change in distribution of dendrite branching in layer 4 stellate cells.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Experiments performed in vitro and in vivo have shown that the presence of afferents and input activity can modulate the patterns in which dendrites differentiate.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Little is known about the process by which dendrites orient themselves in vivo and are compelled to create the intricate branching pattern unique to each specific neuronal class.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] One theory on the mechanism of dendritic arbor development is the synaptotropic hypothesis.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] The synaptotropic hypothesis proposes that input from a presynaptic to a postsynaptic cell, and maturation of excitatory synaptic inputs, eventually can change the course of synapse formation at dendritic and axonal arbors.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] This synapse formation is required for the development of neuronal structure in the functioning brain.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] A balance between metabolic costs of dendritic elaboration and the need to cover the receptive field presumably determine the size and shape of dendrites.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] A complex array of extracellular and intracellular cues modulate dendrite development - including transcription factors, receptor-ligand interactions, various signaling pathways, local translational machinery, cytoskeletal elements, golgi outposts, and endosomes.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] These contribute to the organization of the dendrites on individual cell bodies and the placement of these dendrites in the neuronal circuitry.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] For example, it was shown that β-actin zip code binding protein 1 (ZBP1), contributes to proper dendritic branching.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Dendritic arborization has been found to be induced in cerebellum Purkinje cells by substance P.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Important secretory and endocytic pathways controlling the dendritic development include DAR3 /SAR1, DAR2/Sec23, DAR6/Rab1, etc....
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] All these molecules interplay with each other in controlling dendritic morphogenesis including the acquisition of type specific dendritic arborization, the regulation of dendrite size and the organization of dendrites emanating from different neurons.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Dendritic arborization, also known as dendritic branching, is a multi-step biological process by which neurons form new dendritic trees and branches to create new synapses.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Dendrites in many organisms assume different morphological patterns of branching.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] The morphology of dendrites such as branch density and grouping patterns are highly correlated to the function of the neuron.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Malformation of dendrites is also tightly correlated to impaired nervous system function.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Branching morphologies may assume an *adendritic* structure (not having a branching structure, or not tree-like), or a tree-like radiation structure.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] The structure and branching of a neuron's dendrites, as well as the availability and variation of voltage-gated ion conductance, strongly influences how the neuron integrates the input from other neurons.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] This integration is both temporal, involving the summation of stimuli that arrive in rapid succession, as well as spatial, entailing the aggregation of excitatory and inhibitory inputs from separate branches.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Dendrites were once thought to merely convey electrical stimulation passively.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] This passive transmission means that voltage changes measured at the cell body are the result of activation of distal synapses propagating the electric signal towards the cell body without the aid of voltage-gated ion channels.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Passive cable theory describes how voltage changes at a particular location on a dendrite transmit this electrical signal through a system of converging dendrite segments of different diameters, lengths, and electrical properties.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Based on passive cable theory one can track how changes in a neuron's dendritic morphology impact the membrane voltage at the cell body, and thus how variation in dendrite architectures affects the overall output characteristics of the neuron.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Dendrite radius has notable effects on resistance to electrical current, which in turn affects conduction time and speed.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Dendrite branching optimizes of energy efficiency while maintaining functional connectivity by minimizing power and emphasizing effective signal transmission, supporting their roles in signal integration over longer times.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] This behavior seen in dendrites differs from that in axons, which give more priority to conduction time (and speed).
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Such tradeoffs influence overall neuronal structures, leading to a scaling relationship between conduction time and body size.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Action potentials initiated at the axon hillock propagate back into the dendritic arbor.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] These back-propagating action potentials depolarize the dendritic membrane and provide a crucial signal for synapse modulation and long-term potentiation.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Back-propagation is not completely passive, but modulated by the presence of dendritic voltage-gated potassium channels.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Furthermore, in certain types of neurons, a train of back-propagating action potentials can induce a calcium action potential (a dendritic spike) at dendritic initiation zones.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Dendrites release a multitude of neuroactive substances that are not confined to specific neurotransmitter class, signaling molecule, or brain area.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Dendrites are seen releasing neurotransmitters such as dopamine, GABA, and glutamate in a retrograde fashion.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] In the hypothalamo-neurohypophysial peptide system, oxytocin, and vasopressin (antidiuretic hormone or ADH) are notable neuropeptides that are released from the dendrites of magnocellular neurosecretory cells (MCNs), allowing them to quickly enter the bloodstream.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Paraventricular nuclei also release oxytocin and ADH from dendrites, allowing for the regulation of the anterior pituitary gland, as well as modulation of the parasympathetic and sympathetic changes in organs such as the heart and kidneys.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] This is done by parvocellular neurosecretory and parvocellular preautonomic neurons, respectively.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] In the nigrostriatal and mesolimbic systems, dopamine is released from dendrites in midbrain dopamine neurons, influencing reward and emotion processing, as well as learning and memory.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Loss of dopamine from in the nigrostriatal pathway affects neuronal activity from the basal ganglia, therefore playing a role in the onset of neurodegenerative diseases such as Parkinson's.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Dendritic release of oxytocin, ADH, and dopamine have been found to have both autocrine and paracrine effects on the neuron itself (and nearby glia), as well as on afferent nerve terminals.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Through dendrites complex, polarized structures, changes are closely linked to many neurodegenerative diseases.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Due to the necessity of dendrites for neural function, damage and abnormalities in these components are likely to play a key role in disease development.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Dendritic growth under normal conditions such as cytoskeletal elements and organelles within dendrites contribute to the knowledge of disruption in these components that lead to neurodegenerative pathologies.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Dendrites themselves appear to be capable of plastic changes during the adult life of animals, including invertebrates.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Neuronal dendrites have various compartments known as functional units that are able to compute incoming stimuli.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] These functional units are involved in processing input and are composed of the subdomains of dendrites such as spines, branches, or groupings of branches.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Therefore, plasticity that leads to changes in the dendrite structure will affect communication and processing in the cell.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] During development, dendrite morphology is shaped by intrinsic programs within the cell's genome and extrinsic factors such as signals from other cells.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] However, in adult life, extrinsic signals become more influential and cause more significant changes in dendrite structure compared to intrinsic signals during development.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] In females, the dendritic structure can change as a result of physiological conditions induced by hormones during periods such as pregnancy, lactation, and following the estrous cycle.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] This is particularly visible in pyramidal cells of the CA1 region of the hippocampus, where the density of dendrites can vary up to 30%.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Recent experimental observations suggest that adaptation is performed in the neuronal dendritic trees, where the timescale of adaptation was observed to be as low as several seconds.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Certain machine learning architectures based on dendritic trees have been shown to simplify the learning algorithm without affecting performance.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Most excitatory neurons receive synaptic inputs across their dendritic branches, which results in electrical and biochemical compartmentalization, allowing for a phenomenon known as dendritic spikes, where local regenerative potentials contribute to plasticity.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] In pyramidal neurons dendritic trees have two main functions that allow them to demonstrate an electrical and biochemical compartmentalization that may integrate synaptic inputs prior to transmission to the soma, as well as make up computation units in the brain.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] The first main function allows for differential synaptic processing due to distribution of synaptic inputs across the dendritic branches.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] The processing of these synaptic inputs often involve feedforward or feedback mechanisms that vary based on the type of neuron or brain region.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] The opposite but combined functions of feedforward and feedback processes at different times is proposed to associate different information streams that determine neural selectivity to different stimuli.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] The second function of dendritic trees in this regard is their ability to shape signal propagation that allows for sub-cellular compartmentalization.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Large depolarizations can lead to local regenerative potentials, which may allow neurons to transition from stages of isolated dendritic events (segregation) to combined dendritic events (integration).
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Dendritic compartmentalization has implications in information processing, where it serves as a foundation of trans-neuron signaling, processing stimuli, computation, neuronal expressivity, and mitigating neuronal noise.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Likewise, this phenomenon also underlies the storage of information by optimizing learning capacity and storage capacity.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] In other types of neurons, such as those of the medial superior olive, have differing dendritic properties that allow for coincidence detection.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] In contrast, in retinal ganglion cells, dendritic integration is used for computing directional selectivity, allowing neurons to respond to direction of movement.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Therefore dendritic trees serve various purposes in integrating and processing various different types of stimuli and underlie various neurological processes.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Dendrite dysfunction and alterations in dendrite morphology may contribute to many neuropathies and diseases.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Changes in dendrite morphology may include alterations in branching patterns, fragmentation, loss of branching, and alterations in spine morphology and number.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Such abnormalities contribute to a wide range of neurodevelopmental and neurodegenerative disorders such as autism spectrum disorders (ASDs), schizophrenia, down syndrome, fragile X syndrome, Alzheimer's disease (AD), and more.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] For example, subjects with ASD were observed to have reduced dendrite branching in the CA1 and CA4 regions of the hippocampus, in addition to increased spine density.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] In Rett Syndrome, researchers have observed less dendrite branching in the basal dendrites of the motor cortex and subiculum.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] In schizophrenic patients, reduced dendritic arbor (the tree-like network of dendrites) and spine density were observed.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] In addition to psychological and neurodevelopmental disorders, dendrite dysfunction has also been seen to have implications in onset of neurodegenerative diseases such as Alzheimer's.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] Alzheimer's patients have been observed to have significant changes in dendritic arbor, as well as smaller dendrite lengths in the apical and basal trees of the CA1a and CA1b areas of the hippocampus.
[src:neuron-biology/dendrite] As such, there is much continuous research exploring the effects of dysfunction in dendritic branching and morphology, and scientists continue to expand their study in this field to better understand the basis of various neurological disorders.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] The ensheathed segments are separated at regular short unmyelinated intervals, called nodes of Ranvier.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Each node of Ranvier is around one micrometre long.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Nodes of Ranvier enable a much faster rate of conduction known as saltatory conduction where the action potential recharges at each node to jump over to the next node, and so on until it reaches the axon terminal.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] At the terminal the action potential provokes the release of neurotransmitters across the synapse, which bind to receptors on the post-synaptic cell such as another neuron, myocyte or secretory cell.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Myelin is made by specialized non-neuronal glial cells, that provide insulation, and nutritional and homeostatic support, along the length of the axon.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] In the central nervous system, myelination is formed by glial cells called oligodendrocytes, each of which sends out cellular extensions known as foot processes to myelinate multiple nearby axons.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] In the peripheral nervous system, myelin is formed by Schwann cells, which myelinate only a section of an axon.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] In the central nervous system (CNS), axons carry electrical signals from one nerve cell body to another.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Due to its high prevalence, multiple sclerosis, which specifically affects the central nervous system, is the best known demyelinating disorder.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Myelin was first described as white matter fibres in the 16th century by Vesalius, but the word *myelin* was coined by Rudolf Virchow in 1854.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] The term comes from the Greek word *myelos*, meaning bone marrow, due to the similar color and texture.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Over a century later, following the development of electron microscopy, its glial cell origin, and its ultrastructure became apparent.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Myelin is found in all vertebrates except the jawless fish.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Myelin in the central nervous system differs slightly in composition and configuration from myelin in the peripheral nervous system (PNS), but both perform the same functions of insulation and nutritional support.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Being rich in lipid, myelin appears white, hence its earlier name of white matter of the CNS.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Both CNS white matter tracts such as the corpus callosum, and corticospinal tract, and PNS nerves such as the sciatic nerve, and the auditory nerve, which also appear white, comprise thousands to millions of axons, largely aligned in parallel.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] In the corpus callosum there are more than 200 million axons.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Blood vessels provide the route for oxygen and energy substrates such as glucose to reach these fibre tracts, which also contain other cell types including astrocytes and microglia in the CNS and macrophages in the PNS.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] In terms of total mass, myelin comprises approximately 40% water; the dry mass comprises between 60% and 75% lipid and between 15% and 25% protein.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] In the PNS, myelin protein zero (MPZ or P0) has a similar role to that of PLP in the CNS in that it is involved in holding together the multiple concentric layers of glial cell membrane that constitute the myelin sheath.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] The primary lipid of myelin is a glycolipid called galactocerebroside.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] The intertwining hydrocarbon chains of sphingomyelin strengthen the myelin sheath.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Cholesterol is an essential lipid component of myelin, without which myelin fails to form.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Myelin-associated glycoprotein (MAG) is a critical protein in the formation and maintenance of myelin sheaths.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] MAG is localized on the inner membrane of the myelin sheath and interacts with axonal membrane proteins to attach the myelin sheath to the axon.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Mutations to the MAG gene are implicated in demyelination diseases such as multiple sclerosis.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] The main purpose of myelin is to increase the speed at which electrical impulses (known as action potentials) propagate along the myelinated fiber.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] In unmyelinated fibers, action potentials travel as continuous waves, but, in myelinated fibers, they "hop" or propagate by saltatory conduction.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] The latter is markedly faster than the former, at least for axons over a certain diameter.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Myelin decreases capacitance and increases electrical resistance across the axonal membrane (the axolemma).
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] It has been suggested that myelin permits larger body size by maintaining agile communication between distant body parts.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Myelinated fibers lack voltage-gated sodium channels along the myelinated internodes, exposing them only at the nodes of Ranvier.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Here, they are highly abundant and densely packed.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Positively charged sodium ions can enter the axon through these voltage-gated channels, leading to depolarisation of the membrane potential at the node of Ranvier.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] The resting membrane potential is then rapidly restored due to positively charged potassium ions leaving the axon through potassium channels.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] The sodium ions inside the axon then diffuse rapidly through the axoplasm (axonal cytoplasm), to the adjacent myelinated internode and ultimately to the next (distal) node of Ranvier, triggering the opening of the voltage gated sodium channels and entry of sodium ions at this site.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Although the sodium ions diffuse through the axoplasm rapidly, diffusion is decremental by nature, thus nodes of Ranvier have to be (relatively) closely spaced, to secure action potential propagation.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] The action potential "recharges" at consecutive nodes of Ranvier as the axolemmal membrane potential depolarises to approximately +35 mV.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Along the myelinated internode, energy-dependent sodium/potassium pumps pump the sodium ions back out of the axon and potassium ions back into the axon to restore the balance of ions between the intracellular (inside the cell, i.e. axon in this case) and extracellular (outside the cell) fluids.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Whilst the role of myelin as an "axonal insulator" is well-established, other functions of myelinating cells are less well known or only recently established.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] In 2012, evidence came to light to support a role for the myelinating cell in "feeding" the axon.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] In other words, the myelinating cell seems to act as a local "fueling station" for the axon, which uses a great deal of energy to restore the normal balance of ions between it and its environment, following the generation of action potentials.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] When a peripheral nerve fiber is severed, the myelin sheath provides a track along which regrowth can occur.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] However, the myelin layer does not ensure a perfect regeneration of the nerve fiber.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Some regenerated nerve fibers do not find the correct muscle fibers, and some damaged motor neurons of the peripheral nervous system die without regrowth.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Damage to the myelin sheath and nerve fiber is often associated with increased functional insufficiency.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Unmyelinated fibers and myelinated axons of the mammalian central nervous system do not regenerate.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] The process of generating myelin is called myelination or *myelinogenesis*.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] In the CNS, oligodendrocyte progenitor cells differentiate into mature oligodendrocytes, which form myelin.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] In humans, myelination begins early in the third trimester which starts at around week 26 of gestational age.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] The signal for myelination comes from the axon; axons larger than 1–2 μms become myelinated.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] The length of the internode is determined by the size of the axonal diameter.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] During infancy, myelination progresses rapidly, with increasing numbers of axons acquiring myelin sheaths.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] This corresponds with the development of cognitive and motor skills, including language comprehension, speech acquisition, crawling and walking.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Myelination continues through adolescence and early adulthood and although largely complete at this time, myelin sheaths can be added in grey matter regions such as the cerebral cortex, throughout life.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] For example, in the PNS, a large proportion of axons are unmyelinated.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Instead, they are ensheathed by non-myelinating Schwann cells known as Remak SCs and arranged in Remak bundles.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] In the CNS, non-myelinated axons (or intermittently myelinated axons, meaning axons with long non-myelinated regions between myelinated segments) intermingle with myelinated ones and are entwined, at least partially, by the processes of another type of glial cell the astrocyte.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] People with pernicious anaemia can also develop nerve damage if the condition is not diagnosed quickly.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Subacute combined degeneration of spinal cord secondary to pernicious anaemia can lead to slight peripheral nerve damage to severe damage to the central nervous system, affecting speech, balance, and cognitive awareness.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] When myelin degrades, conduction of signals along the nerve can be impaired or lost, and the nerve eventually withers.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] A more serious case of myelin deterioration is called Canavan disease.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] The immune system may play a role in demyelination associated with such diseases, including inflammation causing demyelination by overproduction of cytokines via upregulation of tumor necrosis factor or interferon.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] MRI evidence that docosahexaenoic acid DHA ethyl ester improves myelination in generalized peroxisomal disorders.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Demyelination results in diverse symptoms determined by the functions of the affected neurons.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] It disrupts signals between the brain and other parts of the body; symptoms differ from patient to patient, and have different presentations upon clinical observation and in laboratory studies.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Research to repair damaged myelin sheaths is ongoing.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Techniques include surgically implanting oligodendrocyte precursor cells in the central nervous system and inducing myelin repair with certain antibodies.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] While results in mice have been encouraging (via stem cell transplantation), whether this technique can be effective in replacing myelin loss in humans is still unknown.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Cholinergic treatments, such as acetylcholinesterase inhibitors (AChEIs), may have beneficial effects on myelination, myelin repair, and myelin integrity.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Increasing cholinergic stimulation also may act through subtle trophic effects on brain developmental processes and particularly on oligodendrocytes and the lifelong myelination process they support.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Increasing oligodendrocyte cholinergic stimulation, AChEIs, and other cholinergic treatments, such as nicotine, possibly could promote myelination during development and myelin repair in older age.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Glycogen synthase kinase 3β inhibitors such as lithium chloride have been found to promote myelination in mice with damaged facial nerves.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Cholesterol is a necessary nutrient for the myelin sheath, along with vitamin B12.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Dysmyelination is characterized by a defective structure and function of myelin sheaths; unlike demyelination, it does not produce lesions.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Such defective sheaths often arise from genetic mutations affecting the biosynthesis and formation of myelin.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] The shiverer mouse represents one animal model of dysmyelination.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Human diseases where dysmyelination has been implicated include leukodystrophies (Pelizaeus–Merzbacher disease, Canavan disease, phenylketonuria) and schizophrenia.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] Functionally equivalent myelin-like sheaths are found in several invertebrate taxa, including oligochaete annelids, and crustacean taxa such as penaeids, palaemonids, and calanoids.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] These myelin-like sheaths share several structural features with the sheaths found in vertebrates including multiplicity of membranes, condensation of membrane, and nodes.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] However, the nodes in vertebrates are annular; i.e. they encircle the axon.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] In contrast, nodes found in the sheaths of invertebrates are either annular or fenestrated; i.e. they are restricted to "spots".
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] It is found on the median giant fiber of the earthworm (*Lumbricus terrestris L.*), which is myelinated with openings on the dorsal side.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] The fastest recorded conduction speed (across both vertebrates and invertebrates) is found in the ensheathed axons of the Kuruma shrimp, an invertebrate, ranging between 90 and 200 m/s.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] This is obtained by neurons 10 μm in diameter and covered by a 10 μm thick myelin.
[src:neuron-biology/myelin] 100–120 m/s for the fastest myelinated vertebrate axon).
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] A **neuron** (American English), **neurone** (British English), or **nerve cell**, is a cell that is excitable, firing electric signals called action potentials across a neural network in the nervous system, mainly in the central nervous system, and helps to receive and conduct impulses.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Neurons communicate with other cells via synapses, which are specialized connections that commonly use minute amounts of chemical neurotransmitters to pass the electric signal from the presynaptic neuron to the target cell through the synaptic gap.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Neurons are the main components of nervous tissue in all animals except sponges and placozoans.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Plants and fungi do not have nerve cells.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Molecular evidence suggests that the ability to generate electric signals first appeared in evolution some 700 to 800 million years ago, during the Tonian period.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Predecessors of neurons were the peptidergic secretory cells.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] They eventually gained new gene modules which enabled cells to create post-synaptic scaffolds and ion channels that generate fast electrical signals.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The ability to generate electric signals was a key innovation in the evolution of the nervous system.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Neurons are typically classified into three types based on their function.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Sensory neurons respond to stimuli such as touch, sound, or light that affect the cells of the sensory organs, and they send signals to the spinal cord and then to the sensorial area in the brain.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Motor neurons receive signals from the brain and spinal cord to control everything from muscle contractions to glandular output.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Interneurons connect neurons to other neurons within the same region of the brain or spinal cord.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] When multiple neurons are functionally connected together, they form what is called a neural circuit.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] A neuron contains all the structures of other cells such as a nucleus, mitochondria, and Golgi bodies, but has additional unique structures such as an axon, and dendrites.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The soma or cell body, is a compact structure, and the axon and dendrites are filaments extruding from the soma.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Dendrites typically branch profusely and extend a few hundred micrometers from the soma.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The axon leaves the soma at a swelling called the axon hillock and travels for as far as 1 meter in humans or more in other species.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] It branches but usually maintains a constant diameter.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] At the farthest tip of the axon's branches are axon terminals, where the neuron can transmit a signal across the synapse to another cell.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Neurons may lack dendrites or have no axons.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The term neurite is used to describe either a dendrite or an axon, particularly when the cell is undifferentiated.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Most neurons receive signals via the dendrites and soma and send out signals down the axon.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] At the majority of synapses, signals cross from the axon of one neuron to the dendrite of another.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] However, synapses can connect an axon to another axon or a dendrite to another dendrite.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The signaling process is partly electrical and partly chemical.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Neurons are electrically excitable, due to the maintenance of voltage gradients across their membranes.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] If the voltage changes by a large enough amount over a short interval, the neuron generates an all-or-nothing electrochemical pulse called an action potential.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] This potential travels rapidly along the axon and activates synaptic connections as it reaches them.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Synaptic signals may be excitatory or inhibitory, increasing or reducing the net voltage that reaches the soma.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] In most cases, neurons are generated by neural stem cells during brain development and childhood.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Neurogenesis largely ceases during adulthood in most areas of the brain.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Neurons are the primary components of the nervous system, along with the glial cells that give them structural and metabolic support.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The nervous system is made up of the central nervous system, which includes the brain and spinal cord, and the peripheral nervous system, which includes the autonomic, enteric and somatic nervous systems.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] In vertebrates, the majority of neurons belong to the central nervous system, but some reside in peripheral ganglia, and many sensory neurons are situated in sensory organs such as the retina and cochlea.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Axons may bundle into nerve fascicles that make up the nerves in the peripheral nervous system (like strands of wire that make up a cable).
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] In the central nervous system bundles of axons are called nerve tracts.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Neurons are highly specialized for the processing and transmission of cellular signals.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Given the diversity of functions performed in different parts of the nervous system, there is a wide variety in their shape, size, and electrochemical properties.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] For instance, the soma of a neuron can vary from 4 to 100 micrometers in diameter.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The accepted view of the neuron attributes dedicated functions to its various anatomical components; however, dendrites and axons often act in ways contrary to their so-called main function.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Axons and dendrites in the central nervous system are typically only about one micrometer thick, while some in the peripheral nervous system are much thicker.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The soma is usually about 10–25 micrometers in diameter and often is not much larger than the cell nucleus it contains.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The longest axon of a human motor neuron can be over a meter long, reaching from the base of the spine to the toes.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Sensory neurons can have axons that run from the toes to the posterior column of the spinal cord, over 1.5 meters in adults.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Giraffes have single axons several meters in length running along the entire length of their necks.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Much of what is known about axonal function comes from studying the squid giant axon, an ideal experimental preparation because of its relatively immense size (0.5–1 millimeter thick, several centimeters long).
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Fully differentiated neurons are permanently postmitotic however, stem cells present in the adult brain may regenerate functional neurons throughout the life of an organism (see neurogenesis).
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Astrocytes are star-shaped glial cells that have been observed to turn into neurons by virtue of their stem cell-like characteristic of pluripotency.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Like all animal cells, the cell body of every neuron is enclosed by a plasma membrane, a bilayer of lipid molecules with many types of embedded protein structures.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] A lipid bilayer is a powerful electrical insulator, but in neurons, many of the protein structures embedded in the membrane are electrically active.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] These include ion channels that permit electrically charged ions to flow across the membrane and ion pumps that chemically transport ions from one side of the membrane to the other.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Most ion channels are gated, permeable only to specific types of ions.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Some ion channels are voltage gated, meaning that they can be switched between open and closed states by altering the voltage difference across the membrane.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Others are chemically gated, meaning that they can be switched between open and closed states by interactions with chemicals that diffuse through the extracellular fluid.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The ions include sodium, potassium, chloride, and calcium.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The interactions between ion channels and ion pumps produce a voltage difference across the membrane, typically a little less than 1/10 of a volt at baseline.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] This voltage has two functions: first, it provides a power source for an assortment of voltage-dependent protein machineries that are embedded in the membrane; second, it provides a basis for electrical signal transmission between different parts of the membrane.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Numerous microscopic clumps called Nissl bodies (or Nissl substance) are seen when nerve cell bodies are stained with a basophilic ("base-loving") dye.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] These structures consist of rough endoplasmic reticulum and associated ribosomal RNA.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Named after German psychiatrist and neuropathologist Franz Nissl (1860–1919), they are involved in protein synthesis and their prominence can be explained by the fact that nerve cells are very metabolically active.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Basophilic dyes such as aniline or (weakly) hematoxylin highlight negatively charged components, and so bind to the phosphate backbone of the ribosomal RNA.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The cell body of a neuron is supported by a complex mesh of structural proteins called neurofilaments, which together with neurotubules (neuronal microtubules) are assembled into larger neurofibrils.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Some neurons also contain pigment granules, such as neuromelanin (a brownish-black pigment that is byproduct of synthesis of catecholamines), and lipofuscin (a yellowish-brown pigment), both of which accumulate with age.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Other structural proteins that are important for neuronal function are actin and the tubulin of microtubules.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Class III β-tubulin is found almost exclusively in neurons.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Actin is predominately found at the tips of axons and dendrites during neuronal development.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] There the actin dynamics can be modulated via an interplay with microtubule.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] There are different internal structural characteristics between axons and dendrites.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Typical axons seldom contain ribosomes, except some in the initial segment.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Dendrites contain granular endoplasmic reticulum or ribosomes, in diminishing amounts as the distance from the cell body increases.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Neurons vary in shape and size and can be classified by their morphology and function.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The anatomist Camillo Golgi grouped neurons into two types; type I with long axons used to move signals over long distances and type II with short axons, which can often be confused with dendrites.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Type I cells can be further classified by the location of the soma.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The basic morphology of type I neurons, represented by spinal motor neurons, consists of a cell body called the soma and a long thin axon covered by a myelin sheath.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The dendritic tree wraps around the cell body and receives signals from other neurons.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The end of the axon has branching axon terminals that release neurotransmitters into a gap called the synaptic cleft between the terminals and the dendrites of the next neuron.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Some unique neuronal types can be identified according to their location in the nervous system and distinct shape.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Afferent and efferent also refer generally to neurons that, respectively, bring information to or send information from the brain.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] A neuron affects other neurons by releasing a neurotransmitter that binds to chemical receptors.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The effect on the postsynaptic neuron is determined by the type of receptor that is activated, not by the presynaptic neuron or by the neurotransmitter.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Receptors are classified broadly as *excitatory* (causing an increase in firing rate), *inhibitory* (causing a decrease in firing rate), or *modulatory* (causing long-lasting effects not directly related to firing rate).
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The two most common (90%+) neurotransmitters in the brain, glutamate and GABA, have largely consistent actions.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Glutamate acts on several types of receptors and has effects that are excitatory at ionotropic receptors and a modulatory effect at metabotropic receptors.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Similarly, GABA acts on several types of receptors, but all of them have inhibitory effects (in adult animals, at least).
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Because of this consistency, it is common for neuroscientists to refer to cells that release glutamate as "excitatory neurons", and cells that release GABA as "inhibitory neurons".
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Some other types of neurons have consistent effects, for example, "excitatory" motor neurons in the spinal cord that release acetylcholine, and "inhibitory" spinal neurons that release glycine.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The distinction between excitatory and inhibitory neurotransmitters is not absolute.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Rather, it depends on the class of chemical receptors present on the postsynaptic neuron.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] In principle, a single neuron, releasing a single neurotransmitter, can have excitatory effects on some targets, inhibitory effects on others, and modulatory effects on others still.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] For example, photoreceptor cells in the retina constantly release the neurotransmitter glutamate in the absence of light.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] So-called OFF bipolar cells are, like most neurons, excited by the released glutamate.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] However, neighboring target neurons called ON bipolar cells are instead inhibited by glutamate, because they lack typical ionotropic glutamate receptors and instead express a class of inhibitory metabotropic glutamate receptors.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] When light is present, the photoreceptors cease releasing glutamate, which relieves the ON bipolar cells from inhibition, activating them; this simultaneously removes the excitation from the OFF bipolar cells, silencing them.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] It is possible to identify the type of inhibitory effect a presynaptic neuron will have on a postsynaptic neuron, based on the proteins the presynaptic neuron expresses.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Parvalbumin-expressing neurons typically dampen the output signal of the postsynaptic neuron in the visual cortex, whereas somatostatin-expressing neurons typically block dendritic inputs to the postsynaptic neuron.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Neurons have intrinsic electroresponsive properties like intrinsic transmembrane voltage oscillatory patterns.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Neurotransmitters are chemical messengers passed from one neuron to another neuron or to a muscle cell or gland cell.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Acetylcholine is released from presynaptic neurons into the synaptic cleft.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] It acts as a ligand for both ligand-gated ion channels and metabotropic (GPCRs) muscarinic receptors.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Nicotinic receptors are pentameric ligand-gated ion channels composed of alpha and beta subunits that bind nicotine.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Ligand binding opens the channel causing the influx of Na+ depolarization and increases the probability of presynaptic neurotransmitter release.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Acetylcholine is synthesized from choline and acetyl coenzyme A.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Noradrenaline (norepinephrine) is released from most postganglionic neurons in the sympathetic nervous system onto two sets of GPCRs: alpha adrenoceptors and beta adrenoceptors.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Noradrenaline is one of the three common catecholamine neurotransmitters, and the most prevalent of them in the peripheral nervous system; as with other catecholamines, it is synthesized from tyrosine.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] GABA is one of two neuroinhibitors in the central nervous system (CNS), along with glycine.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] GABA has a homologous function to ACh, gating anion channels that allow Cl− ions to enter the post synaptic neuron.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Cl− causes hyperpolarization within the neuron, decreasing the probability of an action potential firing as the voltage becomes more negative (for an action potential to fire, a positive voltage threshold must be reached).
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] GABA is synthesized from glutamate neurotransmitters by the enzyme glutamate decarboxylase.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Glutamate is one of two primary excitatory amino acid neurotransmitters, along with aspartate.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Glutamate receptors are one of four categories, three of which are ligand-gated ion channels and one of which is a G-protein coupled receptor (often referred to as GPCR).
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] cation channels mediating fast excitatory synaptic transmission.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] NMDA receptors are another cation channel that is more permeable to Ca2+.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The function of NMDA receptors depends on glycine receptor binding as a co-agonist within the channel pore.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] NMDA receptors do not function without both ligands present.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Metabotropic receptors, GPCRs modulate synaptic transmission and postsynaptic excitability.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] entering the post synaptic neuron and cell damage.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Dopamine is a neurotransmitter that acts on D1 type (D1 and D5) Gs-coupled receptors, which increase cAMP and PKA, and D2 type (D2, D3, and D4) receptors, which activate Gi-coupled receptors that decrease cAMP and PKA.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Dopamine is connected to mood and behavior and modulates both pre- and post-synaptic neurotransmission.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Loss of dopamine neurons in the substantia nigra has been linked to Parkinson's disease.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Dopamine is synthesized from the amino acid tyrosine.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Tyrosine is catalyzed into levodopa (or L-DOPA) by tyrosine hydroxylase, and levodopa is then converted into dopamine by the aromatic amino acid decarboxylase.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Serotonin (5-Hydroxytryptamine, 5-HT) can act as excitatory or inhibitory.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Of its four 5-HT receptor classes, 3 are GPCR and 1 is a ligand-gated cation channel.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Serotonin is synthesized from tryptophan by tryptophan hydroxylase, and then further by decarboxylase.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] A lack of 5-HT at postsynaptic neurons has been linked to depression.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Drugs that block the presynaptic serotonin transporter are used for treatment, such as Prozac and Zoloft.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] ATP is a neurotransmitter acting at both ligand-gated ion channels (P2X receptors) and GPCRs (P2Y) receptors.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] ATP is, however, best known as a cotransmitter.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Such purinergic signaling can also be mediated by other purines like adenosine, which particularly acts at P2Y receptors.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Histamine is a monoamine neurotransmitter and neuromodulator.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Histamine-producing neurons are found in the tuberomammillary nucleus of the hypothalamus.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Histamine is involved in arousal and regulating sleep/wake behaviors.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Since 2012 there has been a push from the cellular and computational neuroscience community to come up with a universal classification of neurons that will apply to all neurons in the brain as well as across species.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] This is done by considering the three essential qualities of all neurons: electrophysiology, morphology, and the individual transcriptome of the cells.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Besides being universal this classification has the advantage of being able to classify astrocytes as well.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] A method called patch-sequencing in which all three qualities can be measured at once is used extensively by the Allen Institute for Brain Science.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] In 2023, a comprehensive cell atlas of the adult, and developing human brain at the transcriptional, epigenetic, and functional levels was created through an international collaboration of researchers using the most cutting-edge molecular biology approaches.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Neurons communicate with each other via synapses, where either the axon terminal of one cell contacts another neuron's dendrite, soma, or, less commonly, axon.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Neurons such as Purkinje cells in the cerebellum can have over 1000 dendritic branches, making connections with tens of thousands of other cells; other neurons, such as the magnocellular neurons of the supraoptic nucleus, have only one or two dendrites, each of which receives thousands of synapses.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Synapses can be excitatory or inhibitory, either increasing or decreasing activity in the target neuron, respectively.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Some neurons also communicate via electrical synapses, which are direct, electrically conductive junctions between cells.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] When an action potential reaches the axon terminal, it opens voltage-gated calcium channels, allowing calcium ions to enter the terminal.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Calcium causes synaptic vesicles filled with neurotransmitter molecules to fuse with the membrane, releasing their contents into the synaptic cleft.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The neurotransmitters diffuse across the synaptic cleft and activate receptors on the postsynaptic neuron.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] High cytosolic calcium in the axon terminal triggers mitochondrial calcium uptake, which, in turn, activates mitochondrial energy metabolism to produce ATP to support continuous neurotransmission.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] An autapse is a synapse in which a neuron's axon connects to its dendrites.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The human brain has some 8.6 × 1010 (eighty six billion) neurons.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Each neuron has on average 7,000 synaptic connections to other neurons.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] It has been estimated that the brain of a three-year-old child has about 1015 synapses (1 quadrillion).
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] This number declines with age, stabilizing by adulthood.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Estimates vary for an adult, ranging from 1014 to 5 × 1014 synapses (100 to 500 trillion).
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] They can also get modulated by input from the environment and hormones released from other parts of the organism, which could be influenced more or less directly by neurons.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] This also applies to neurotrophins such as BDNF.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The gut microbiome is also connected with the brain.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Neurons also communicate with microglia, the brain's main immune cells via specialized contact sites, called "somatic junctions".
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] These connections enable microglia to constantly monitor and regulate neuronal functions, and exert neuroprotection when needed.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] In 1937 John Zachary Young suggested that the squid giant axon could be used to study neuronal electrical properties.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] It is larger than but similar to human neurons, making it easier to study.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] By inserting electrodes into the squid giant axons, accurate measurements were made of the membrane potential.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The cell membrane of the axon and soma contain voltage-gated ion channels that allow the neuron to generate and propagate an electrical signal (an action potential).
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Some neurons also generate subthreshold membrane potential oscillations.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] These signals are generated and propagated by charge-carrying ions including sodium (Na+), potassium (K+), chloride (Cl−), and calcium (Ca2+).
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Several stimuli can activate a neuron leading to electrical activity, including pressure, stretch, chemical transmitters, and changes in the electric potential across the cell membrane.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Stimuli cause specific ion-channels within the cell membrane to open, leading to a flow of ions through the cell membrane, changing the membrane potential.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Neurons must maintain the specific electrical properties that define their neuron type.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Thin neurons and axons require less metabolic expense to produce and carry action potentials, but thicker axons convey impulses more rapidly.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] To minimize metabolic expense while maintaining rapid conduction, many neurons have insulating sheaths of myelin around their axons.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The sheaths are formed by glial cells: oligodendrocytes in the central nervous system and Schwann cells in the peripheral nervous system.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The sheath enables action potentials to travel faster than in unmyelinated axons of the same diameter, whilst using less energy.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The myelin sheath in peripheral nerves normally runs along the axon in sections about 1 mm long, punctuated by unsheathed nodes of Ranvier, which contain a high density of voltage-gated ion channels.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Multiple sclerosis is a neurological disorder that results from the demyelination of axons in the central nervous system.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Some neurons do not generate action potentials but instead generate a graded electrical signal, which in turn causes graded neurotransmitter release.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Such non-spiking neurons tend to be sensory neurons or interneurons, because they cannot carry signals long distances.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Neural coding is concerned with how sensory and other information is represented in the brain by neurons.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The main goal of studying neural coding is to characterize the relationship between the stimulus and the individual or ensemble neuronal responses and the relationships among the electrical activities of the neurons within the ensemble.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] It is thought that neurons can encode both digital and analog information.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The conduction of nerve impulses is an example of an all-or-none response.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] In other words, if a neuron responds at all, then it must respond completely.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Greater intensity of stimulation, like brighter image/louder sound, does not produce a stronger signal but can increase firing frequency.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Receptors respond in different ways to stimuli.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Slowly adapting or tonic receptors respond to a steady stimulus and produce a steady rate of firing.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Tonic receptors most often respond to increased stimulus intensity by increasing their firing frequency, usually as a power function of stimulus plotted against impulses per second.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] This can be likened to an intrinsic property of light where greater intensity of a specific frequency (color) requires more photons, as the photons cannot become "stronger" for a specific frequency.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Other receptor types include quickly adapting or phasic receptors, where firing decreases or stops with a steady stimulus; examples include skin which, when touched causes neurons to fire, but if the object maintains even pressure, the neurons stop firing.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The neurons of the skin and muscles that are responsive to pressure and vibration have filtering accessory structures that aid their function.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The pacinian corpuscle is one such structure.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] It has concentric layers like an onion, which form around the axon terminal.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] When pressure is applied and the corpuscle is deformed, mechanical stimulus is transferred to the axon, which fires.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] If the pressure is steady, the stimulus ends; thus, these neurons typically respond with a transient depolarization during the initial deformation and again when the pressure is removed, which causes the corpuscle to change shape again.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Other types of adaptation are important in extending the function of several other neurons.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Additionally, the analog information carried in the Action Potential has been shown to be able to survive and travel distances originally not thought to be possible.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] This has been proposed to be a highly effective way to encode information compared to the usual rate and temporal coding theories commonly seen in the literature, with the ability to transfer around 4 times more information than current wisdom would suggest.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The German anatomist Heinrich Wilhelm Waldeyer introduced the term *neuron* in 1891, based on the ancient Greek νεῦρον *neuron* 'sinew, cord, nerve'.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The word was adopted in French with the spelling *neurone*.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] That spelling was also used by many writers in English, but has now become rare in American usage and uncommon in British usage.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Some previous works used *nerve cell* (*cellule nervose*), as adopted in Camillo Golgi's 1873 paper on the discovery of the silver staining technique used to visualize nervous tissue under light microscopy.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The neuron's place as the primary functional unit of the nervous system was first recognized in the late 19th century through the work of the Spanish anatomist Santiago Ramón y Cajal.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] To make the structure of individual neurons visible, Ramón y Cajal improved a silver staining process that had been developed by Camillo Golgi.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The improved process involves a technique called "double impregnation" and is still in use.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] In 1888 Ramón y Cajal published a paper about the bird cerebellum.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] In this paper, he stated that he could not find evidence for anastomosis between axons and dendrites and called each nervous element "an autonomous canton." This became known as the neuron doctrine, one of the central tenets of modern neuroscience.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] In 1891, the German anatomist Heinrich Wilhelm Waldeyer wrote a highly influential review of the neuron doctrine in which he introduced the term *neuron* to describe the anatomical and physiological unit of the nervous system.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The silver impregnation stains are a useful method for neuroanatomical investigations because, for reasons unknown, it stains only a small percentage of cells in a tissue, exposing the complete micro structure of individual neurons without much overlap from other cells.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The neuron doctrine is the now fundamental idea that neurons are the basic structural and functional units of the nervous system.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The theory was put forward by Santiago Ramón y Cajal in the late 19th century.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] It held that neurons are discrete cells (not connected in a meshwork), acting as metabolically distinct units.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Later discoveries yielded refinements to the doctrine.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] For example, glial cells, which are non-neuronal, play an essential role in information processing.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Also, electrical synapses are more common than previously thought, comprising direct, cytoplasmic connections between neurons; In fact, neurons can form even tighter couplings: the squid giant axon arises from the fusion of multiple axons.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Ramón y Cajal also postulated the Law of Dynamic Polarization, which states that a neuron receives signals at its dendrites and cell body and transmits them, as action potentials, along the axon in one direction: away from the cell body.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The Law of Dynamic Polarization has important exceptions; dendrites can serve as synaptic output sites of neurons and axons can receive synaptic inputs.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Although neurons are often described as "fundamental units" of the brain, they perform internal computations.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Neurons integrate input within dendrites, and this complexity is lost in models that assume neurons to be a fundamental unit.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Dendritic branches can be modeled as spatial compartments, whose activity is related to passive membrane properties, but may also be different depending on input from synapses.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Compartmental modelling of dendrites is especially helpful for understanding the behavior of neurons that are too small to record with electrodes, as is the case for *Drosophila melanogaster*.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The number of neurons in the brain varies dramatically from species to species.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] In a human, there are an estimated 10–20 billion neurons in the cerebral cortex and 55–70 billion neurons in the cerebellum.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] By contrast, the nematode worm *Caenorhabditis elegans* has just 302 neurons, making it an ideal model organism as scientists have been able to map all of its neurons.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The fruit fly *Drosophila melanogaster*, a common subject in biological experiments, has around 100,000 neurons and exhibits many complex behaviors.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Many properties of neurons, from the type of neurotransmitters used to ion channel composition, are maintained across species, allowing scientists to study processes occurring in more complex organisms in much simpler experimental systems.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Charcot–Marie–Tooth disease (CMT) is a heterogeneous inherited disorder of nerves (neuropathy) that is characterized by loss of muscle tissue and touch sensation, predominantly in the feet and legs extending to the hands and arms in advanced stages.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Presently incurable, this disease is one of the most common inherited neurological disorders, affecting 36 in 100,000 people.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Alzheimer's disease (AD), also known simply as *Alzheimer's*, is a neurodegenerative disease characterized by progressive cognitive impairment, together with declining activities of daily living and neuropsychiatric symptoms or behavioral changes.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The most striking early symptom is loss of short-term memory (amnesia), which usually manifests as minor forgetfulness that becomes steadily more pronounced with illness progression, with relative preservation of older memories.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] As the disorder progresses, cognitive (intellectual) impairment extends to the domains of language (aphasia), skilled movements (apraxia), and recognition (agnosia), and functions such as decision-making and planning become impaired.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Parkinson's disease (PD), also known as *Parkinson's*, is a degenerative disorder of the central nervous system that often impairs motor skills and speech.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Parkinson's disease belongs to a group of conditions called movement disorders.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] It is characterized by muscle rigidity, tremor, a slowing of physical movement (bradykinesia), and in extreme cases, a loss of physical movement (akinesia).
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The primary symptoms are the results of decreased stimulation of the motor cortex by the basal ganglia, normally caused by the insufficient formation and action of dopamine, which is produced in the dopaminergic neurons of the brain.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Secondary symptoms may include high-level cognitive dysfunction and subtle language problems.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Myasthenia gravis is a neuromuscular disease leading to fluctuating muscle weakness and fatigability during simple activities.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Weakness is typically caused by circulating antibodies that block acetylcholine receptors at the postsynaptic neuromuscular junction, inhibiting the stimulative effect of the neurotransmitter acetylcholine.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Myasthenia is treated with immunosuppressants, cholinesterase inhibitors and, in selected cases, thymectomy.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Demyelination is a process characterized by the gradual loss of the myelin sheath enveloping nerve fibers.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] When myelin deteriorates, signal conduction along nerves can be significantly impaired or lost, and the nerve eventually withers.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Demyelination may affect both central and peripheral nervous systems, contributing to various neurological disorders such as multiple sclerosis, Guillain-Barré syndrome, and chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Although demyelination is often caused by an autoimmune reaction, it may also be caused by viral infections, metabolic disorders, trauma, and some medications.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Although most injury responses include a calcium influx signaling to promote resealing of severed parts, axonal injuries initially lead to acute axonal degeneration, which is the rapid separation of the proximal and distal ends, occurring within 30 minutes of injury.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Degeneration follows with swelling of the axolemma, and eventually leads to bead-like formation.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Granular disintegration of the axonal cytoskeleton and inner organelles occurs after axolemma degradation.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Early changes include accumulation of mitochondria in the paranodal regions at the site of injury.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The endoplasmic reticulum degrades and mitochondria swell up and eventually disintegrate.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The disintegration is dependent on ubiquitin and calpain proteases (caused by the influx of calcium ions), suggesting that axonal degeneration is an active process that produces complete fragmentation.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The process takes about roughly 24 hours in the PNS and longer in the CNS.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The signaling pathways leading to axolemma degeneration are unknown.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Neurons develop through the process of neurogenesis, in which neural stem cells divide to produce differentiated neurons.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Once fully differentiated they are no longer capable of undergoing mitosis.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Neurogenesis primarily occurs during embryonic development.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Neurons initially develop from the neural tube in the embryo.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The neural tube has three layers – a ventricular zone, an intermediate zone, and a marginal zone.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The ventricular zone surrounds the tube's central canal and becomes the ependyma.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Dividing cells of the ventricular zone form the intermediate zone which stretches to the outermost layer of the neural tube called the pial layer.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The gray matter of the brain is derived from the intermediate zone.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The extensions of the neurons in the intermediate zone make up the marginal zone when myelinated becomes the brain's white matter.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Differentiation of the neurons is ordered by their size.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Smaller sensory neurons together with glial cell differentiate at birth.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Adult neurogenesis can occur and studies of the age of human neurons suggest that this process occurs only for a minority of cells and that the vast majority of neurons in the neocortex form before birth and persist without replacement.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The extent to which adult neurogenesis exists in humans, and its contribution to cognition are controversial, with conflicting reports published in 2018.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] The body contains a variety of stem cell types that can differentiate into neurons.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Researchers found a way to transform human skin cells into nerve cells using transdifferentiation, in which "cells are forced to adopt new identities".
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] During neurogenesis in the mammalian brain, progenitor and stem cells progress from proliferative divisions to differentiative divisions.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] This progression leads to the neurons and glia that populate cortical layers.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Epigenetic modifications play a key role in regulating gene expression in differentiating neural stem cells, and are critical for cell fate determination in the developing and adult mammalian brain.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Epigenetic modifications include DNA cytosine methylation to form 5-methylcytosine and 5-methylcytosine demethylation.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] DNA cytosine methylation is catalyzed by DNA methyltransferases (DNMTs).
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Methylcytosine demethylation is catalyzed in several stages by TET enzymes that carry out oxidative reactions (e.g.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] 5-methylcytosine to 5-hydroxymethylcytosine) and enzymes of the DNA base excision repair (BER) pathway.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] At different stages of mammalian nervous system development, two DNA repair processes are employed in the repair of DNA double-strand breaks.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Intercellular communication between developing neurons and microglia is also indispensable for proper neurogenesis and brain development.
[src:neuron-biology/neuron] Peripheral axons can regrow if they are severed, but one neuron cannot be functionally replaced by one of another type (Llinás' law).
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The nodes are primarily composed of sodium and potassium voltage-gated ion channels; CAMs such as neurofascin-186 and NrCAM; and cytoskeletal adaptor proteins such as ankyrin-G and spectrinβIV.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] Many vertebrate axons are surrounded by a myelin sheath, allowing rapid and efficient saltatory ("jumping") propagation of action potentials.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The contacts between neurons and glial cells display a very high level of spatial and temporal organization in myelinated fibers.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The myelinating glial cells - oligodendrocytes in the central nervous system (CNS), and Schwann cells in the peripheral nervous system (PNS) - are wrapped around the axon, leaving the axolemma relatively uncovered at the regularly spaced nodes of Ranvier.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The internodal glial membranes are fused to form compact myelin, whereas the cytoplasm-filled paranodal loops of myelinating cells are spirally wrapped around the axon at both sides of the nodes.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] This organization demands a tight developmental control and the formation of a variety of specialized zones of contact between different areas of the myelinating cell membrane.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] Each node of Ranvier is flanked by paranodal regions where helicoidally wrapped glial loops are attached to the axonal membrane by a septate-like junction.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The segment between nodes of Ranvier is termed as the internode, and its outermost part that is in contact with paranodes is referred to as the juxtaparanodal region.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The nodes are encapsulated by microvilli stemming from the outer aspect of the Schwann cell membrane in the PNS, or by perinodal extensions from astrocytes in the CNS.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The internodes are the myelin segments and the gaps between are referred to as nodes.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The size and the spacing of the internodes vary with the fiber diameter in a curvilinear relationship that is optimized for maximal conduction velocity.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The size of the nodes span from 1–2 μm whereas the internodes can be up to (and occasionally even greater than) 1.5 millimetres long, depending on the axon diameter and fiber type.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The structure of the node and the flanking paranodal regions are distinct from the internodes under the compact myelin sheath, but are very similar in CNS and PNS.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The axon is exposed to the extra-cellular environment at the node and is constricted in its diameter.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The decreased axon size reflects a higher packing density of neurofilaments in this region, which are less heavily phosphorylated and are transported more slowly.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] Vesicles and other organelles are also increased at the nodes, which suggest that there is a bottleneck of axonal transport in both directions as well as local axonal-glial signaling.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] When a longitudinal section is made through a myelinating Schwann cell at the node, three distinctive segments are represented: the stereotypic internode, the paranodal region, and the node itself.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] In the internodal region, the Schwann cell has an outer collar of cytoplasm, a compact myelin sheath, and inner collar of cytoplasm, and the axolemma.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] At the paranodal regions, the paranodal cytoplasm loops contact thickenings of the axolemma to form septate –like junctions.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] In the node alone, the axolemma is contacted by several Schwann microvilli and contains a dense cytoskeletal undercoating.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] Although freeze fracture studies have revealed that the nodal axolemma in both the CNS and PNS is enriched in intra-membranous particles (IMPs) compared to the internode, there are some structural differences reflecting their cellular constituents.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] In the PNS, specialized microvilli project from the outer collar of Schwann cells and come very close to nodal axolemma of large fibers.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The projections of the Schwann cells are perpendicular to the node and are radiating from the central axons.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] However, in the CNS, one or more of the astrocytic processes come in close vicinity of the nodes.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] Researchers declare that these processes stem from multi-functional astrocytes, as opposed to from a population of astrocytes dedicated to contacting the node.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] On the other hand, in the PNS, the basal lamina that surrounds the Schwann cells is continuous across the node.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] A study suggests that in the CNS, nerve cells individually alter the size of the nodes to tune conduction speeds, leading node length to vary much more across different axons than within one.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The nodes of Ranvier Na+/Ca2+ exchangers and high density of voltage-gated Na+ channels that generate action potentials.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] A sodium channel consists of a pore-forming α subunit and two accessory β subunits, which anchor the channel to extra-cellular and intra-cellular components.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The nodes of Ranvier in the central and peripheral nervous systems mostly consist of αNaV1.6 and β1 subunits.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The extra-cellular region of β subunits can associate with itself and other proteins, such as tenascin R and the cell-adhesion molecules neurofascin and contactin.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] Contactin is also present at nodes in the CNS and interaction with this molecule enhances the surface expression of Na+ channels.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] Ankyrin has been found to be bounded to βIV spectrin, a spectrin isoform enriched at nodes of Ranvier and axon initial segments.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The PNS nodes are surrounded by Schwann cell microvilli, which contain ERMs and EBP50 that may provide a connection to actin microfilaments.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] Several extracellular matrix proteins are enriched at nodes of Ranvier, including tenascin-R, Bral-1, and proteoglycan NG2, as well as phosphacan and versican V2.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] At CNS nodes, the axonal proteins also include contactin; however, different from the PNS, Schwann cell microvilli are replaced by astrocyte perinodal extensions.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The molecular organization of the nodes corresponds to their specialized function in impulse propagation.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The level of sodium channels in the node versus the internode suggests that the number IMPs corresponds to sodium channels.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] Potassium channels are essentially absent in the nodal axolemma, whereas they are highly concentrated in the paranodal axolemma and Schwann cell membranes at the node.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The exact function of potassium channels have not quite been revealed, but it is known that they may contribute to the rapid repolarization of the action potentials or play a vital role in buffering the potassium ions at the nodes.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] This highly asymmetric distribution of voltage-gated sodium and potassium channels is in striking contrast to their diffuse distribution in unmyelinated fibers.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The filamentous network subjacent to the nodal membrane contains cytoskeletal proteins called spectrin and ankyrin.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The high density of ankyrin at the nodes may be functionally significant because several of the proteins that are populated at the nodes share the ability to bind to ankyrin with extremely high affinity.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] All of these proteins, including ankyrin, are enriched in the initial segment of axons which suggests a functional relationship.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] Now the relationship of these molecular components to the clustering of sodium channels at the nodes is still not known.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] Although some cell-adhesion molecules have been reported to be present at the nodes inconsistently; however, a variety of other molecules are known to be highly populated at the glial membranes of the paranodal regions where they contribute to its organization and structural integrity.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The complex changes that the Schwann cell undergoes during the process of myelination of peripheral nerve fibers have been observed and studied by many.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The initial envelopment of the axon occurs without interruption along the entire extent of the Schwann cell.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] This process is sequenced by the in-folding of the Schwann cell surface so that a double membrane of the opposing faces of the in-folded Schwann cell surface is formed.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] This membrane stretches and spirally wraps itself over and over as the in-folding of the Schwann cell surface continues.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] As a result, the increase in the thickness of the extension of the myelin sheath in its cross-sectional diameter is easily ascertained.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] It is also evident that each of the consecutive turns of the spiral increases in size along the length of the axon as the number of turns increase.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] However, it is not clear whether or not the increase in length of the myelin sheath can be accounted solely by the increase in length of axon covered by each successive turn of the spiral, as previously explained.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] At the junction of two Schwann cells along an axon, the directions of the lamellar overhang of the myelin endings are of opposite sense.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] This junction, adjacent of the Schwann cells, constitutes the region designated as the node of Ranvier.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] Researchers prove that in the developing CNS, Nav1.2 is initially expressed at all forming nodes of Ranvier.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] Upon maturation, nodal Nav1.2 is down-regulated and replaced by Nav1.6.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] Nav1.2 is also expressed during PNS node formation, which suggests that the switching of Nav-channel subtypes is a general phenomenon in the CNS and PNS.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] In this same investigation, it was shown that Nav1.6 and Nav1.2 colocalize at many nodes of Ranvier during early myelination.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] This also led to the suggestion that early clusters of Nav1.2 and Nav1.6 channels are destined to later become nodes of Ranvier.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] Neurofascin is also reported to be one of the first proteins to accumulate at newly forming nodes of Ranvier.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] They are also found to provide the nucleation site for attachment of ankyrin G, Nav channels, and other proteins.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The recent identification of the Schwann cell microvilli protein gliomedin as the likely binding partner of axonal neurofascin brings forward substantial evidence for the importance of this protein in recruiting Nav channels to the nodes of Ranvier.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] Furthermore, *Lambert et al.* and *Eshed et al.* also indicates that neurofascin accumulates before Nav channels and is likely to have crucial roles in the earliest events associated with node of Ranvier formation.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] Thus, multiple mechanisms may exist and work synergistically to facilitate clustering of Nav channels at nodes of Ranvier.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The first event appears to be the accumulation of cell adhesion molecules such as NF186 or NrCAM.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The intra-cellular regions of these cell-adhesion molecules interact with ankyrin G, which serves as an anchor for sodium channels.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] In the PNS, this interaction has been elucidated.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The Ig superfamily membrane protein NrCAM acts as a pioneer molecule in the formation of the nodes by recruiting ankyrin-G, a mediator protein in the connection of actin-spectrin cytoskeleton to the ion gated channels present at the node.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] At the same time, the periaxonal extension of the glial cell wraps around the axon, giving rise to the paranodal regions.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] This movement along the axon contributes significantly to the overall formation of the nodes of Ranvier by permitting heminodes formed at the edges of neighboring glial cells to fuse into complete nodes.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] Septate-like junctions form at the paranodes with the enrichment of NF155 in glial paranodal loops.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] Immediately following the early differentiation of the nodal and paranodal regions, potassium channels, Caspr2 and TAG1 accumulate in the juxta-paranodal regions.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] This accumulation coincides directly with the formation of compact myelin.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] In mature nodal regions, interactions with the intracellular proteins appear vital for the stability of all nodal regions.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] In the CNS, oligodendrocytes do not possess microvilli, but appear capable to initiate the clustering of some axonal proteins through secreted factors.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The combined effects of such factors with the subsequent movements generated by the wrapping of oligodendrocyte periaxonal extension could account for the organization of CNS nodes of Ranvier.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] An action potential is a spike of both positive and negative ionic discharge that travels along the membrane of a cell.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The creation and conduction of action potentials represents a fundamental means of communication in the nervous system.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] Action potentials represent rapid reversals in voltage across the plasma membrane of axons.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] These rapid reversals are mediated by voltage-gated ion channels found in the plasma membrane.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The action potential travels from one location in the cell to another, but ion flow across the membrane occurs only at the nodes of Ranvier.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] As a result, the action potential signal jumps along the axon, from node to node, rather than propagating smoothly, as they do in axons that lack a myelin sheath.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The clustering of voltage-gated sodium and potassium ion channels at the nodes permits this behavior.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] Since an axon can be unmyelinated or myelinated, the action potential has two methods to travel down the axon.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] These methods are referred to as continuous conduction for unmyelinated axons, and saltatory conduction for myelinated axons.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] Saltatory conduction is defined as an action potential moving in discrete jumps down a myelinated axon.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] This process is outlined as the charge passively spreading to the next node of Ranvier to depolarize it to threshold which will then trigger an action potential in this region which will then passively spread to the next node and so on.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] Saltatory conduction provides one advantage over conduction that occurs along an axon without myelin sheaths.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] This is that the increased speed afforded by this mode of conduction assures faster interaction between neurons.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] On the other hand, depending on the average firing rate of the neuron, calculations show that the energetic cost of maintaining the resting potential of oligodendrocytes can outweigh the energy savings of action potentials.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] So, axon myelination does not necessarily save energy.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] Mitochondria and other membranous organelles are normally enriched in the PNP region of peripheral myelinated axons, especially those large caliber axons.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The actual physiological role of this accumulation and factors that regulate it are not understood; however, it is known that mitochondria are usually present in areas of the cell that expresses a high energy demand.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] In these same regions, they are also understood to contain growth cones, synaptic terminals, and sites of action potential initiation and regeneration, such as the nodes of Ranvier.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] In the synaptic terminals, mitochondria produce the ATP needed to mobilize vesicles for neurotransmission.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] In the nodes of Ranvier, mitochondria serve as an important role in impulse conduction by producing the ATP that is essential to maintain the activity of energy-demanding ion pumps.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] Supporting this fact, about five times more mitochondria are present in the PNP axoplasm of large peripheral axons than in the corresponding internodal regions of these fibers.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] Saltatory conduction in myelinated axons requires organization of the nodes of Ranvier, whereas voltage-gated sodium channels are highly populated.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] Studies show that αII-Spectrin, a component of the cytoskeleton is enriched at the nodes and paranodes at early stages and as the nodes mature, the expression of this molecule disappears.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] It is also proven that αII-Spectrin in the axonal cytoskeleton is absolutely vital for stabilizing sodium channel clusters and organizing the mature node of Ranvier.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] It has been shown previously that OMgp (oligodendrocyte myelin glycoprotein) clusters at nodes of Ranvier and may regulate paranodal architecture, node length and axonal sprouting at nodes.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The proteins in these excitable domains of neuron when injured may result in cognitive disorders and various neuropathic ailments.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] The myelin sheath of long nerves was discovered and named by German pathological anatomist Rudolf Virchow in 1854.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] French pathologist and anatomist Louis-Antoine Ranvier later discovered the nodes, or gaps, in the myelin sheath that now bear his name.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] Born in Lyon, Ranvier was one of the most prominent histologists of the late 19th century.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] Ranvier abandoned pathological studies in 1867 and became an assistant of physiologist Claude Bernard.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] He was the chairman of General Anatomy at the Collège de France in 1875.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] Using staining techniques developed by Ludwig Mauthner, he noticed that myelinated axons were only stained at regular intervals, leading to the discovery of the nodes.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] Reportedly, he dismissed the idea of nodes in the CNS although their existence was proven later.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] His refined histological techniques and his work on both injured and normal nerve fibers became world-renowned.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] His observations on fiber nodes and the degeneration and regeneration of cut fibers had a great influence on Parisian neurology at the Salpêtrière.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] Soon afterwards, he discovered gaps in sheaths of nerve fibers, which were later called the Nodes of Ranvier.
[src:neuron-biology/node-of-ranvier] This discovery later led Ranvier to careful histological examination of myelin sheaths and Schwann cells.
[src:neuron-biology/soma-biology] In cellular neuroscience, the **soma** (pl.: **somata** or **somas**; from Greek σῶμα*(sôma)* 'body'), or **cell body**, is the bulbous, non-process portion of a neuron or glial cell that contains the cell nucleus.
[src:neuron-biology/soma-biology] The part of the soma without the nucleus is called the **perikaryon** (pl.: **perikarya**).
[src:neuron-biology/soma-biology] The soma of a neuron (i.e., the main part of the neuron in which the dendrites branch off of) contains many organelles, including granules called Nissl granules, which are composed largely of rough endoplasmic reticulum and free polyribosomes.
[src:neuron-biology/soma-biology] The cell nucleus is a key feature of the soma.
[src:neuron-biology/soma-biology] The nucleus is the source of most of the RNA that is produced in neurons.
[src:neuron-biology/soma-biology] In general, most proteins are produced from mRNAs that do not travel far from the cell nucleus.
[src:neuron-biology/soma-biology] This creates a challenge for supplying new proteins to axon endings that can be a meter or more away from the soma.
[src:neuron-biology/soma-biology] Axons contain microtubule-associated motor proteins that transport protein-containing vesicles between the soma and the synapses at the axon terminals.
[src:neuron-biology/soma-biology] Such transport of molecules towards and away from the soma maintains critical cell functions.
[src:neuron-biology/soma-biology] In case of neurons, the soma receives a large number of inhibitory synapses, which can regulate the activity of these cells.
[src:neuron-biology/soma-biology] It has also been shown that microglial processes constantly monitor neuronal functions through somatic junctions, and exert neuroprotection when needed.
[src:neuron-biology/soma-biology] Intermediate filaments are abundant in both perikarya and axonal and dendritic processes and are called neurofilaments.
[src:neuron-biology/soma-biology] The neurofilaments become cross linked with certain fixatives and when impregnated with silver, they form neurofibrils visible with the light microscope.
[src:neuron-biology/soma-biology] The axon hillock is a specialized domain of the neuronal cell body from which the axon originates.
[src:neuron-biology/soma-biology] A high amount of protein synthesis occurs in this region, as it contains many Nissl granules (which are ribosomes wrapped in RER) and polyribosomes.
[src:neuron-biology/soma-biology] Within the axon hillock, materials are sorted as either items that will enter the axon (like the components of the cytoskeletal architecture of the axon, mitochondria, etc.) or will remain in the soma.
[src:neuron-biology/soma-biology] In addition, the axon hillock also has a specialized plasma membrane that contains large numbers of voltage-gated ion channels, since this is most often the site of action potential initiation and triggering.
[src:neuron-biology/soma-biology] The survival of some sensory neurons depends on axon terminals making contact with sources of survival factors that prevent apoptosis.
[src:neuron-biology/soma-biology] The survival factors are neurotrophic factors, including molecules such as nerve growth factor (NGF).
[src:neuron-biology/soma-biology] NGF interacts with receptors at axon terminals, and this produces a signal that must be transported up the length of the axon to the nucleus.
[src:neuron-biology/soma-biology] A 2004 theory of how such survival signals are sent from axon endings to the soma includes the idea that NGF receptors are endocytosed from the surface of axon tips and that such endocytotic vesicles are transported up the axon.
